net.akami.mask.tree

Class BinaryTree<T extends Branch>

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.akami.mask.tree.BinaryTree<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - what kind of branch will be handled by the tree.
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.lang.Iterable<T>
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    CalculationTree

    public abstract class BinaryTree<T extends Branch>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Iterable<T>
    A Binary tree handles branch splitting, evaluating and merging with the defined behaviours.

    When instantiating a BinaryTree, note that the splitting should automatically and instantly be performed in the begin(Branch), starting off with the given branch.
    This begin(Branch) method must define how a branch must be divided according to ALL the splitters, whereas split(Branch, char...) defines how each branch must be divided, according to the splitter(s) given.

    In other words, the begin method defines how and with which parameter the split method will be called. Note that BinaryTree implements Iterable, so that you can actually use for each loops with it.
    Author:
    Antoine Tran

        public BinaryTree(java.lang.String expression,

        splitters - the chars used to split the tree, see begin(Branch) for further information.

        protected abstract void begin(T self)

        Parameters:

        Parameters:

        by - the 'splitters', which are used to determine the left and right part of the branch

      • evalBranch

        protected abstract void evalBranch(T self)

        Parameters:
        self - the branch itself

      • merge

        public Expression merge()
        Merges the whole tree. The usual behavior is to go from the last branch to the first one, see if the current actually is calculable, and if yes then calls the evalBranch(Branch) method.
        If the finalResult method does not return an empty optional, the value found is returned
        Note that the merge method can be redefined if the behavior does not suits the tree.
        Returns:
        the reduced value of the first branch, while finalResult() is not redefined
